    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-01-07T03:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-01-07T03:00:00-05:00" n="4"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d4">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/13879: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Nanking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-01-07T16:00:00+08:00"
                            >January 7, 1937—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received January 7—2:45 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>7. Under date of January 5 the National Government issued Mandates making changes
                    in important administrative and military posts in Shensi and Kansu. Yang Hu
                    Cheng although temporarily left at his post was cashiered. The Embassy learns
                    from official sources that Yang is not disposed to accept the new situation and
                    the National Government is moving troops and artillery along the railway toward
                    Sian to enforce its orders. The Embassy has learned also from various Chinese
                    official sources and indirectly from a foreign observer that Communist influence
                    is very strong in Sian. Exact information regarding present conditions there is
                    impossible to obtain and I have today telegraphed to Swenson, Scandinavian
                    Alliance Mission, Sian, asking for a report. It is doubtful, however, whether
                    this effort will be successful. The Embassy is endeavoring to discover means of
                    evacuating American citizens from Sian in view of probable hostilities but this
                    seems impossible at the present time.<note n="16" xml:id="d4fn16">See also <ref
                            target="frus1937v04#pg_236">vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">iv</hi>, pp.
                            236</ref> ff.</note>
                </p>
                <p>Sent to the Department, Peiping, Hankow, Shanghai.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
